description: Cophixalus exiguus, commonly known as the tiny rain frog, is a species of frog in the family Microhylidae.
This species is native to tropical rainforests in New Guinea and parts of surrounding regions.
Cophixalus exiguus is known for its small size and its ability to adapt to humid, forested environments.
It has a distinctive appearance with a dark brown body and lighter markings, blending well with its natural habitat.
Like many other species in the genus Cophixalus, it is arboreal, spending much of its time in the trees.
Due to habitat destruction and climate change, this species may be facing threats, though it is currently not listed as endangered.
Cophixalus infacetus, also known as the rough-sided rain frog, is a species of frog in the family Microhylidae.
It is native to the rainforests of New Guinea, where it is commonly found in humid, forested areas.
The species is characterized by its small size and rough, granular skin, which helps it blend into its environment.
Cophixalus infacetus is arboreal, often found in the trees and shrubs of its rainforest habitat.
This frog species is nocturnal, typically becoming active at night to hunt for small invertebrates.
Like other species in the genus Cophixalus, it faces threats from habitat loss, but its conservation status remains uncertain.

It is found in the rainforests of New Guinea and surrounding islands, where it inhabits humid, tropical environments.
The species is named for its distinctive, ornamental appearance, with intricate patterns and a rough, granular texture on its skin.
Cophixalus ornatus is typically arboreal, spending much of its time in the trees, but it can also be found in leaf litter on the forest floor.
This frog is nocturnal, foraging at night for insects and other small invertebrates.
While not widely studied, Cophixalus ornatus may be vulnerable to habitat destruction, though it has not been extensively assessed for conservation status.

This bird is found across a wide range of habitats in Australia, including forests, woodlands, and urban areas.
It is characterized by its striking black face and contrasting white underparts, with a greyish back and wings.
Coracina novaehollandiae is a medium-sized passerine bird that feeds primarily on insects, including beetles and caterpillars, as well as some fruits.
This species is known for its distinctive, melodious calls, which it uses to communicate with others, especially during the breeding season.
The Black-faced Cuckoo-shrike is a relatively common and adaptable species, and its population is stable despite habitat changes.

This bird is native to New Guinea, as well as parts of surrounding islands, and is typically found in forests, woodlands, and coastal habitats.
Coracina papuensis is characterized by its distinctive white underparts, with a dark grey upper body, and a slightly forked tail.
It primarily feeds on insects, such as beetles, ants, and caterpillars, but also consumes some fruits and berries.
